<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="033" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Apply ESLint Strictening Fixes to TypeScript Codebase</title>
    <phase>4: Remediation</phase>
    <status>pending</status>
    <estimated-hours>3</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>008, 011</dependencies>
    <blocks>035, 043</blocks>
    <tags>remediation, typescript, linting, eslint</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Apply the strictened ESLint rules configured in task 011 to the existing TypeScript codebase.
    Fix violations introduced by the new stricter rules focusing on four categories: unused variables
    (remove or use them), explicit any replacements (replace `any` with proper types), prefer-const
    (replace `let` with `const` for non-reassigned variables), and no-console removal (replace with
    proper logging or remove debug statements). Use eslint --fix for automatic fixes, then manually
    fix complex cases. Test after fixing each project to verify no runtime behavior changes.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior TypeScript developer specializing in ESLint configuration and type safety. Expert at
    systematic codebase lint cleanup and replacing `any` types with proper TypeScript type annotations.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A TypeScript codebase with zero ESLint violations under the strictened rule set established in
    task 011. All PCF and Code Page projects pass `npx eslint src/client/ --max-warnings 0` cleanly.
    Fixes are safe — no runtime behavior changes — and each project still builds successfully.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Task 011 configured stricter ESLint rules across the TypeScript codebase. These rules likely
      introduced violations in existing code that was written under the previous, less strict
      configuration. This task fixes those violations.

      Focus areas and fix strategies:
      1. Unused variables (@typescript-eslint/no-unused-vars): Either remove the unused variable/import,
         or prefix with underscore (_varName) if it must exist for interface compliance. For unused
         function parameters in callbacks, use the underscore prefix convention.
      2. Explicit any (@typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any): Determine the correct type from usage context.
         If the actual type is unknown at development time, use `unknown` with a type guard instead of
         `any`. For PCF context parameters, consult .claude/adr/ADR-022.md for the correct PCF types.
      3. Prefer-const (prefer-const rule): Auto-fixable. Run `eslint --fix` to convert all `let`
         declarations that are never reassigned to `const`.
      4. No-console (no-console rule): Remove `console.log` debug statements. Replace meaningful
         `console.error` calls with the project's logging pattern (check existing code for the pattern —
         may be a LoggingService or structured logging approach).

      Process: Work project by project (pcf controls first, then code-pages, then shared). Run
      `eslint --fix` on each project first for auto-fixable violations, then manually address
      remaining violations. Build each project after fixing to verify.

      The audit report at projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-typescript-pcf.md
      has the initial violation counts by rule — use this to understand the scope before starting.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/client/pcf/ (modify — fix ESLint violations in PCF controls)</file>
      <file>src/client/code-pages/ (modify — fix ESLint violations in code pages)</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/ (modify — fix ESLint violations in shared library)</file>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-typescript-pcf.md (read — initial violation counts from task 008)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="spec">Fixes MUST NOT change runtime behavior. Only change types and variable declarations — do not alter logic, conditionals, or API calls as part of lint fixes.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Run `npm run build` in each affected project after fixing it to verify the build is clean. Do not proceed to the next project until the current project builds.</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-022">PCF controls use React 16 platform-provided libraries. When replacing `any` types in PCF code, use the correct PCF framework types (ComponentFramework types) — do not use React 18 type definitions.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">For `any` types that genuinely cannot be typed without significant refactoring (e.g., complex discriminated unions from external APIs), add `// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any` with a comment explaining why. This is a last resort — target fewer than 5 suppressions total.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Do not remove console.error calls that are the only error reporting mechanism in a catch block — replace with the project's logging pattern instead. Removing error logging silently breaks observability.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-typescript-pcf.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-022.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-typescript-pcf.md to understand the initial violation counts and which projects have the most violations. Plan the order of remediation (highest violations first for maximum impact).</step>
    <step order="2">Run `npx eslint src/client/ --format compact 2>&1 | wc -l` to get the current total violation count before starting fixes. Record this baseline.</step>
    <step order="3">For the first project (highest violations), run `npx eslint {project-path} --fix` to auto-fix prefer-const and other auto-fixable rules. Run `npm run build` in that project to verify. Commit the auto-fix changes as a batch.</step>
    <step order="4">Manually fix the remaining unused variable violations in the first project: remove dead code, use underscore prefix for interface-required parameters. Build and verify.</step>
    <step order="5">Manually fix explicit any violations in the first project: determine correct types from usage context. Use `unknown` + type guard for genuinely unknown types. Apply sparingly-used eslint-disable comments where no safe type exists. Build and verify.</step>
    <step order="6">Fix no-console violations in the first project: remove debug console.log calls, replace console.error in catch blocks with the project's logging pattern. Build and verify.</step>
    <step order="7">Repeat steps 3-6 for each remaining project (pcf controls, code-pages, shared) in order of violation count.</step>
    <step order="8">Run `npx eslint src/client/ --max-warnings 0` across all client projects to verify the final clean state. Record the final violation count.</step>
    <step order="9">Run `dotnet test` to verify that API-touching TypeScript changes (if any) did not break integration tests.</step>
    <step order="10">Document in a brief note: initial violation count, final violation count, number of eslint-disable suppressions added (with justifications), any violations deferred to future tasks.</step>
    <step order="11">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 033 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="changes">src/client/pcf/ (ESLint violations resolved)</output>
    <output type="changes">src/client/code-pages/ (ESLint violations resolved)</output>
    <output type="changes">src/client/shared/ (ESLint violations resolved)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>`npx eslint src/client/ --max-warnings 0` exits with code 0 (zero violations)</criterion>
    <criterion>All four violation categories addressed: unused variables, explicit any, prefer-const, no-console</criterion>
    <criterion>Fewer than 5 eslint-disable-next-line suppressions added (each with justification comment)</criterion>
    <criterion>No runtime behavior changes: all projects build with `npm run build` after fixes</criterion>
    <criterion>PCF controls use correct PCF framework types (not React 18 types) per ADR-022</criterion>
    <criterion>No console.error calls removed from catch blocks without replacement logging</criterion>
    <criterion>Initial and final violation counts documented</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
